data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both compile and run without issues:

```csharp
Span<nint>  span  = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> uspan = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system each element is 8 bytes (they'd be 4 bytes on a 32-bit runtime). This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5, when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class unmanaged types — and unmanaged types are valid for `stackalloc`.
